collation.p: The manuscript is too fragile to be fully collated. However, as the textblock is more or less entirely detached from the binding, the quires, sixteen in all, can be counted at the spine. The first six quires have catchwords at intervals of 8 leaves, indicating an overall structure of quaternions.

p.note: Top left corner, in brown ink by an early modern hand: No 10; below: Brocmanni; top centre, in brown ink in Brocman's hand, a note identifying the elevation of the feast of St George to festum duplex in November 1415: MCCCCXV in nov. Festivitas S. Georgii mart. ut duplex festum celebretur Stat. Seld. Tit. Hon. p. 574 ed. lat. Bottom of page, in brown ink by an early modern hand: Hunc librum dono mihi dedit pater carissimus .

binding.condition: The textblock is almost entirely detached from the binding. The leather is cracked at the spine and the bottom left front corner is frayed.

origin.p:
Flanders? , 15th century, second half. The prevalence of English saints in the calendar reveals that the Psalter was used in England - more specifically in the dioces of Rochester, as it includes St Ithamar and St Paulinus, both bishops of Rochester. The calendar is discussed in some detail by Richards (1985) as part of a group of related 15th century calendars produced for this dioces. Richards notes that Flemish influence on the decoration and script connects the group and suggests that the calendars were mass-produced by Flemish scribes ( Richards (1985)
). She suggests, furthermore, that the calendar of A 182 may itself have been, or is closely related to, the base text of the group (ibid.).

The inclusion of the feast of St Osmund, canonized in , the Transfiguration, instituted in , and the Feast of the Holy Name, instituted towards the end of the 15th century, indicates a date of later 15th century. While this dating clearly applies to the calendar, Eva Lindqvist Sandgren believes that the style of decoration of the Psalter itself more accurately reflects a production in the first half of the 15th century.

provenance.p: A former owner's note in an early modern hand on states (in Latin) that most beloved father gave me this book, with the name of the donor having been erased.
On , an early modern hand has written in Swedish: Come Holy Spirit Lord God visit our hearts and bestow good spirits upon His Majesty's dutiful servant and a monogram, possibly RO.

Previously no. 10 in the collection of Nils Reinhold Brocman, book collector and librarian at the Royal Library and Antiquities Archive. Upon his death in , a large part of his book collection was donated to the Antiquities Archive.

acquisition.p: Transferred to the National Library from the Antiquities Archive.

p.note: In the margins, psalm numbers in ink in an early modern or near contemporary hand. Psalm 39 erroneously numbered as 29 (). Psalm 108 erroneously numbered as 107 (), and from here until Psalm 118 () the numbering is behind by one, with corrections in pencil by a modern hand below. Psalm 118:17 is numbered as 118 (), 118:33 as 119 (), 118:49 as 120 (), 118:65 as 121 (), 118:81 as 122 (), 118:97 as 123 (), with the modern correcting hand adding 118 from ff. After this, the numbering in ink disappears, but the modern numbering in pencil - now in square brackets - continues from Psalm 119 () until the end.

Covering the top half of the page, in black ink by an early modern hand: Kom Helige Ande Herre God besök wåra hiertan och gif Kongl.a Mai.tts tropliktig tienare godt mod; below, in the same ink and style, a large monogram: RO(?). Bottom right corner, in ink: a word, faded and difficult to make out.
Pen trials in the same hand and style as the recto: Denna and two flourished Rs (or Ks?).

decoDesc.p: Main text in brown ink. Larger decorated initials at Ps. 1, 26, 38, 52, 68, 80, 97, 109, corresponding to the secular cursus (Sunday-Monday matins, and Sunday vespers).

decoNote.p: : illuminated historiated opening initial B over 9 lines in mauve and blue shades alternating in 4 sections, with baubles in the darker shade. Background in gold leaf. In the counter space, king David, crowned and dressed in a blue mantle lined with ermine, seated on a green throne, playing the harp, and surrounded by four attendants dressed in orange and green, one of whom is holding a sword. A pattern of tiles in black and yellow creates a sense of depth in the space. The marginal border consists of thin straight double stalks, where one part is in gold leaf and the other alternates between mauve and blue sections. Soft swirling intertwining acanthus leaves in mainly red/mauve and blue decorate the edges and corners of the stalks. Green and orange occur occasionally. The straight sections between the acanthus leaves are adorned by sheer peacock-imitating feathers with tiny dots in green or gold leaf at the ends. The border fills much of the marginal space, partly due to the secondary trimming of the book pages. All decorations are outlined in black and the coloured areas are highlighted in white. , , , , , , : psalm initials over 6-9 lines; letter bodies alternating in 2-4 sections of mauve and blue shades with baubles in the darker shade ( in all blue). Quadrangular background in gold leaf with small hollowed out roundels at the corners. In the counter space, swirling acanthus leaves mainly in blues and mauves, but also some greens, reds, and yellows. Marginal borders of acanthus leaves, peacock feathers, and small flowers in the same colour scheme extending into and filling the left, upper, and lower margin. All decorations are outlined in black and the colours are highlighted in white. : plain psalm or section initials over 2 lines in blue with flourishing in red extending into the left margin. plain initials over 1 line alternating in red and blue, and on , in blue and gold leaf. : plain capital KL in blue with simple quadrangular pen-flourishing in red at the head of each month.
For further description of the decoration, see Eva Lindqvist Sandgren.
